title: The biggest risks facing cities -- and some solutions

aws-transcripts.transcript: So here's a prediction. If we get our cities right, we just might survive the 21st century. We get him wrong and we're done for. Cities are the most extraordinary experiment in social engineering that we humans have ever come up with. If you live in a city and even if you live in a slum, which 20% of the world's urban population does, you're likely to be healthier, wealthier, better educated and live longer than their country cousins. There's a reason why 3,000,000 people are moving to cities every single week. Cities are where the future happens. First, they're open. They're creative. They're dynamic, their democratic, the cosmopolitan. They're sexy. They're the perfect antidote to reactionary nationalism. But cities have a dark side. They take up just 3% of the world's surface area, but they count for more than 75% of our energy consumption and the mid 80% of our greenhouse gases. There are hundreds of thousands of people who die in our cities every single year from violence and millions more who were killed as a result of car accidents and pollution. In Brazil, where I live, we've got 25 of the 50 most homicidal cities on the planet, and 1/4 of our cities have chronic water shortages. And this in a country with 20% of the known water reserves, the cities are dual edged. Part of the problem is that apart from a handful of mega cities in the West in the Far East, we don't know that much about the thousands of cities in Africa, in Latin America, in Asia, where 90% of all future population growth is set to take place. So why this gnomes gap? What part of the problem is that? We still see the world, the lens of nation states. We're still locked in 1/17 century paradigm, a parochial national sovereignty. And yet, in the 16 hundreds, when nation states were really coming into their own, less than 1% of the world's population resided. In this city. Today it's 54% by 2050 will be closer to 70%. So the world has changed. We have these 193 nation states what we have easily as many cities that are beginning to rival them in power and influence.
